The paper deals with computer vision and robotics in the medical field, specifically in the context of hip surgery. The use of neural networks for segmentation and landmark identification suggests a focus on computer vision (cs.CV). The goal of automatic registration for navigation implies a focus on robotics (cs.RO). The use of machine learning and medical imaging suggests a possible fit with multimedia (cs.MM) and medical imaging (cs.MS) sub-categories. Finally, the mention of interference with surgical workflow and the need for efficient registration suggests a possible fit with human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
